                        <provenance type="found" notBefore="1848">Found, along with Aglish 2 (I-KER-009), by Richard Hitchcock in the graveyard (KE054-032002-) in this townland. This stone was presented on his behalf to the Royal Irish Academy in 1848 by Bishop Graves (Macalister 1945, 137). The second ogham stone is still in situ. Aglish is a probable <ref target="https://monasticon.celt.dias.ie/showrecord.php?id=3540">early church site</ref> with a bullaun also discovered in the graveyard. No trace of a church survives (Cuppage et al 1986, 258).
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed" when="2025">In the collection of the National Museum of Ireland. Currently (July 2025) on display as part of the <ref target="https://www.museum.ie/en-IE/Museums/Archaeology/Exhibitions/Words-on-the-Wave-Ireland-and-St-Gallen-in-Early-M">Words on the Wave Exhibition</ref>. This stone was recorded in 3D in collaboration with the <ref target="https://discoveryprogramme.ie/">Discovery Programme</ref> in 2016 as part of the Ogham in 3D project.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
