           <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
            <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-down"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"/><w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐᚊᚔ</w> <name>ᚋᚐᚊ<supplied reason="lost">ᚔ</supplied><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"/></name> <name>ᚑ<unclear reason="damage">ᚌ</unclear>ᚌᚑᚇᚔ<g ref="#forfid_X"/><supplied reason="lost" cert="medium">ᚐ</supplied></name> 
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-down"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"/><w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MAQI</w> <name>MAQ<supplied reason="lost">I</supplied><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"/></name> <name>O<unclear reason="damage">G</unclear>GODI<g ref="#forfid_X" type="interpretation_K"/><supplied reason="lost" cert="medium">A</supplied></name> 
                </ab>
                 <ab type="list">[---]MAQI MAQ[I---] OG̣GODIK[A]</ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus"/>
                           
            <div type="translation">
                <p>[...] son of <name xml:lang="sga">Mac-[...]</name></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>As noted by McManus (1991, 109): <q>MAQ(Q)I-X names can be distinguished from the patronymic MAQ(Q)I X ("son of X") type either by appearing first on the inscription or (as in this case) by being preceded by MAQ(Q)I ("son of") or some other formula word</q>.</p>
                <p>The last name, or what survives of it, is unclear but Ziegler (1994, 198) suggests that it may be an example of LUGUDECCAS, which is found in a number of other inscriptions.</p>
            </div>
